pages.summary: DISCLAIMER: This write-up is based on the original solution created by the author of the Hammingbird radio-signal CTF challenge you can find it here. Many thanks to @aleand.ro. The purpose of this exercise is to redesign the solution using GNU Radio solely for the purpose of learning more about radio signals, exploring the tool, and having fun. This blog post is written with passion, dedication and a lot of hours debugging GNU Radio.
pages.text:
disclaimer: this write-up is based on the original solution created by the author of the hammingbird radio-signal ctf challenge you can find it here. many thanks to @aleand.ro. the purpose of this exercise is to redesign the solution using gnu radio solely for the purpose of learning more about radio signals, exploring the tool, and having fun. this blog post is written with passion, dedication and a lot of hours debugging gnu radio.
for those who are not familiar with gnu radio, you can find a clear and concise explanation here: https://wiki.gnuradio.org/index.php?title=what_is_gnu_radio
challenge description the hamming bird radio-signal ctf challenge is part of the ctrl-space ctf 2025, a unique cybersecurity competition played on real satellites orbiting earth. the goal of the challenge is to reverse-engineer the radio signal to uncover a secret message hidden within the broadcast transmission.
a flying bird is transmitting some telemetry data; check if any important information has been broadcast!
in offline radio-signal challenges, the player is typically given a complex file captured from radio transmissions. in this case, the input provided is the file rf-dump.complex. the extension already hints that the file could contain a radio signal representation.
let’s load the file into gnu radio using the file source block and observe the frequency span with the qt gui frequency sink. initially, we can set the sample rate to a high value such as 100k. this value should match the expected bandwidth, allowing us to load the entire signal into the frequency spectrum for observation.
as we can see from the frequency plot, the signal is not centered, and two distinct frequency peaks are clearly visible. this is a good indication that the transmitted frequency changes over time, suggesting that an fsk modulation scheme may be used. this behavior can be further examined using the qt gui waterfall sink in gnu radio or with inspectrum, which visualizes how frequency evolves over time.
we can already spot a recurrent pattern at the beginning of the transmission called preamble, very common in radio frequency signals. the preamble is a fixed, repetitive sequence sent by the transmitter to wake up the receiver and synchronize it to the correct bit rate. this sequence is usually something simple and known, such as 1010101010101, marking the beginning of the transmission.
while inspectrum can already help already with some basic demodulation it is still limited in signal processing, therefore, from now on we will use gnu radio.
let’s start! we begin with filtering and re-centering the signal to make later processing steps easier. for this task, we use a frequency-translating fir filter. this block takes two main inputs: a taps function and a center frequency.
while the center frequency parameter is straightforward, the taps function can be less intuitive. in simple terms, the taps define the filter characteristics. for example, the low cutoff, high cutoff, or both, determine which frequency components are allowed to pass through. many others parameters are described in the documentation here.
the fir filter produces a new signal, shown below in the first waterfall plot:
at the top, we can see a clean signal where only the relevant frequencies are passed through.
as observed earlier, we identified that the signal uses fsk modulation, more specifically 2-fsk, based on the two peaks visible in the frequency sink. gnu radio provides a demodulation block called quadrature demod. although it is not designed only for 2-fsk, it can be configured appropriately for that purpose.
in particular, setting the gain parameter to: samp_rate / (2 * math.pi * fsk_deviation) results in correct fsk demodulation. refer to the documentation for a deeper explanation of how this value is derived.
plotting the output of the quadrature demod block reveals an almost “squared” signal, although it is not yet fully clean:
as we can see, we can have already a good view on the demodulated signal and we can already spot some recurring patterns, such as the preamble we previously observed in inspectrum.
so far, we haven’t achieved much more than previously done via inspectrum, but it is here that gnu radio comes into place.
gnu radio post-processing gnu radio can further refine this signal for better processing, one useful block for this purpose is the moving average block. it improves signal squaring but more specifically it performs an average of the value in a specific interval taking out noise.
see below the plotted output: that completed the demodulation part, and in theory we could stop here and do further processing off gnu radio with a python script for example, but i want to provide an extra mile that made my life a bit easier when working with this signal and perhaps can help me in the future while dealing with similar transmissions.
messages extraction and preamble identification one additional step i wanted to implement for this ctf challenge was a reliable method to automatically detect each message, save it as an individual file, and process it independently.
to perform this type of splitting, three modules can be used :
burst tagger tagged file sink complex to mag we can use the magnitude of a signal to identify noise and then tag the sample where the noise starts and finishes. (it may not be the best way to do so but i found it very handy)
this approach becomes very powerful when searching for specific messages or when building post-acquisition routines that operate on a per-packet basis. for example, gnu radio supports custom python modules to process each packet, using tagged samples to determine the start and end of a transmission.
below is an example of a post-processing function that handles tagged samples and processes each captured packet individually:
[...] def work(self, input_items, output_items): inp = input_items[0] n = len(inp) # build dictionary of tags at positions tags = self.get_tags_in_window(0, 0, n) tag_positions = {t.offset - self.nitems_read(0): t for t in tags} for i in range(n): # --------------------------- # tag handling # --------------------------- if i in tag_positions: t = tag_positions[i] key = str(t.key) val = pmt.to_python(t.value) # debug print print("tag:", key, "value:", val) # start burst if key == self.tag_key and val == 1: self.in_burst = true self.current_buf = [] # end burst elif key == self.tag_key and val == 0: self.in_burst = false # convert to numpy array burst = np.array(self.current_buf, dtype=np.float32) self.saved_bursts.append(burst) self.processed_bursts.append(burst) print("captured packet length:", len(burst)) print(f"packets captured{len(self.processed_bursts)}") #print("packet") #print(burst); self.parse(burst) in a nutshell, the python block detects the preamble and uses the provided threshold parameter for similarity estimation. it then decodes the packet using the hamming algorithm and prints the payload to the screen. the full output is available on gnu radio in the console window.
the entire code can be found on my github repository https://github.com/giggi0x00/radio_signal_ctf_ctrl-space_ctf_2025.
conclusion although i was unable to complete the challenge within the allocated time during the ctf, i continued working on it afterwards to learn more about radio signals and, in particular, the gnu radio tool, which can help speed up signal processing without reinventing the wheel. thank you for making it this far! happy hacking!

pages.summary: The purpose of this blog post is to provide a guide on how to prepare a device for fault injection and power analysis attacks. While many blogs focus solely on explaining these attacks, they often overlook the critical preparation phase. We want to showcase a simple hardware modification (but very effective) that will make the attacks to be successful. Within this blog post we will use a classic STM32 development board to demonstrate how to make it susceptible to such attacks.
pages.text:
the purpose of this blog post is to provide a guide on how to prepare a device for fault injection and power analysis attacks. while many blogs focus solely on explaining these attacks, they often overlook the critical preparation phase. we want to showcase a simple hardware modification (but very effective) that will make the attacks to be successful. within this blog post we will use a classic stm32 development board to demonstrate how to make it susceptible to such attacks.
what is power analysis in a nutshell, power analysis attack falls into the category of side channel attacks, where, any emission of the electronic target under analysis can be turned to a powerful source of information. as implied by the name power analysis consists in analyzing the power consumption of the target while performing normal operations. for example, imagine the following piece of code:
void checkpassoword(char *buffer) { int res = strcmp(spassword, buffer); if (res == 0) { unlock_the_secret_garden(); return 0; } //do_nothing.. return 1; } it is quite clear that if the password is correct the target will go through an extra set of instructions before returning, meaning that the power consumption will be higher. we want to spot these differences and understand the code paths and instructions being executed. this can be seen also to a transistor level, where there is a correlation between the power consumption and the operations that device is performing. it is therefore important to ensure that the power consumption associated with each action is accurately measured and free from interference. by “free from interference,” we mean that no additional factors are artificially increasing or decreasing the power used by the device during the analysis. the smallest fluctuations in consumption at low levels need to be emphasized in order to achieve accurate results.
the design of the iot device, for instance, focuses on maintaining stability by ensuring that tasks and operations are consistently performed with a stable and constant voltage output. keeping factors such as digital levels, frequency fluctuations, and power consumption within a trustworthy power level. to achieve so, components like voltage regulator, capacitors, diodes, or transistors play a crucial role.
in order to effectively attack an electronic device, it is crucial to understand its design, identify key components, and make necessary modifications as required.
target of our journey one of the target of our journey is the stm 32 nucleo-64 development board. the board is a low-cost development platform for stm32 microcontrollers, used for prototyping embedded systems, programming firmware, and expanding with peripherals through arduino-compatible connectors. it supports debugging and testing via an integrated st-link, and is popular for iot, automation, and learning purposes. thus, it was used as subject for our analysis.
the components on the board are visible on both sides of the pcb:
we aim to demonstrate a simple power analysis (spa) attack on this board. for this purpose, the board has been programmed with firmware designed to emulate a login prompt which grants access to the main device’s functionalities. the prompt is accessible via the uart interface and the following can be observed in the terminal when a wrong password is typed:
$ sudo socat /dev/ttyusb0,b115200,raw,echo=0,crnl - type your password to unlock the device: aaaaaa access denied! type your password to unlock the device: the attack that will be carried out in order to circumvent this security defense is simple power analysis. the objective is to measure the power consumption of the device while we send different passwords. through a careful analysis will be possible to identify different cycles that a strcmp function will go through on each inputs
preparation of the target [adding also where and how we tap there why are and what we are measuring]
we need to understand the pcb design, components, power lines, sources of randomness, potential security defenses, and any pcb components that could interfere with our attacks.
first of all let’s start by understand the power inputs line of the device. these can be easily identified by following the vcc power lines of our mcu and the available pins.
the board has a publicly available datasheet; however, even without schematics, it is still possible to understand the power lines and make modifications in most cases. as we can see from the following schematic, there are many capacitors connected between the vcc and ground. these capacitors, are meant to stabilize the power of the device, ensuring stability and normal execution conditions ( decoupling capacitor). for our purposes we can consider the the decoupling capacitor as if they are device’s local energy storage.
first schematic, let’s identify the capacitor based on what we have discussed earlier.
even without a schematic, these type of capacitors can be identified using a multimeter and a careful inspection of the pcb design.
these capacitors were marked with yellow dots for identification.
however, we can see that other capacitors are still present on the board. these capacitors are related the power input in the following diagram. while we could also consider to remove them, it is possible to bypass the power circuit line using the jp6 connector and disconnect the power lines from the rest of the circuit. this will allow us to have vcc lines not affected by any electronic components, making possible power analysis possible.
hardware modifications the identified capacitors were disconnected from the board. as you can see from the following pictures only one pin was disconnected. the usage of soldering station or hot air gun could be very useful in these cases.
hardware setup while preparing for the setup, always watch out for ground loop!!!
time to attack the password prompt! the board is now ready to be deeply analyzed for the power consumption, aiming to detect voltage fluctuations based on the execution cycles. the attack consists in attack one single byte of the password at the time. we can suppose that the device will compare the input with some value inside. this means that a routine like the following one could be implemented in the firmware:
void checkpassoword(char *buffer) { int res = strcmp(spassword, buffer); if (res == 0) { //do something } ... } without going to much into the detail of the attack, we can simply understand the attack based on the following calculations:
let’s assume the correct value is amsdata.
we provide the following two inputs: amsaaaa and amddddd. the strcmp function compares each byte sequentially and returns when a match is found or a mismatch occurs. this means that the more correct characters we provide, the more execution cycles strcmp will take to complete, leading to a more power consumption.
to fully understand the value of the hardware analysis and the changes made to the board, some power traces were collected before the modifications were implemented
the power traces correspond to the power measurements of the device while the inputs are being processed.
let’s have a look at how the power traces look like: the power traces before the modification look quite homogeneous, except some random spikes. it is very difficult to identify changes in the pattern across multiple inputs.
the following traces were collected with all capacitors disconnected from the pcb. as you can see, we have similar patterns as before; however, there is a noticeable change in the original power trace that requires further inspection.
if we zoom into the beginning of the diagram, we can observe that the red trace diverges significantly from the rest of the power traces.
final attack will come in the following post… stay tuned!

pages.summary: In this blog post, I will cover all the steps I took to circumvent the Read Out protection mechanism. For those unfamiliar with this security measure deployed by ST to safeguard firmware and customer data, here is a brief explanation from their website:
pages.text:
in this blog post, i will cover all the steps i took to circumvent the read out protection mechanism. for those unfamiliar with this security measure deployed by st to safeguard firmware and customer data, here is a brief explanation from their website:
https://www.st.com/resource/en/product_training/stm32f7_security_memories_protections.pdf: read out protection readout protection, or rdp is a global mechanism that prevents external read access to flash memory, backup sram and registers. an external access can be gained by using a jtag connector, a serial wire port or boot software embedded in sram. three levels of rdp protection are defined from level 0, which offers no protection at all, to level 2 which has full and permanent protection. […] when first rdp level, level 0, is set, the device has no protection. all read or write operations (if no write protection is set) on the flash memory or the backup sram are possible in all boot configurations (flash user boot, debug or boot from ram). option bytes are also changeable in this level.
rdp levels :
level 0 is is the factory default level. in level 1, read protection is set for the flash memory, the backup sram and the backup registers is set. in this level, protected memories are only accessible when booting from user flash memory. whenever a debugger access is detected or boot is not set to a flash memory area, any access to the protected memories generates a system hard fault which blocks all code execution until the next power-on reset* in level 2, all protections from level 1, plus no swd/jtag connection possible, no going back. rdp/wrp option bytes can no longer be changed. stm32 bootloader stm32 provides multiple options for accessing the flash memory. these protocols can be accessed either through the swd interface or a built-in system bootloader, which is available in almost all stm32 devices at address 0x1fff0000. the system bootloader allows users to interact with the stm32 device using various protocols to perform operations such as programming, erasing, or reading memory sectors. the protocols available include swd, spi, uart, and others.
due to its simplicity, this discussion will focus on the uart protocol and how it interfaces with the bootloader.
the following commands are accessible via the uart interface:
without any protection enabled, the read command (0x11) successfully retrieves 256 bytes from the specified page address. however, when read out protection is activated, this operation is rejected. to gain a deeper understanding of how this mechanism is implemented, the system bootloader was reverse-engineered.
we can observe the commands being parsed in the following screenshot:
the function proceeds by checking for the presence of the read out protection mechanism:
this was verified by observing the value read just before the operation. the highlighted address, 0x400023c14, confirms that the system checks the status of the read out protection mechanism.
it becomes evident that, to gain access to the flash memory, the highlighted if statement must be targeted for a fault injection attack.
environment setup the environment consists of the following devices and tools:
stm32f401cc developer board cw1173 chipwhisperer-lite usb-uart ttl converter st link programmer the device was programmed with a dummy firmware for testing and the read out protection was set as shown in the following picture:
before proceeding with the attack, it is important to determine how and when to glitch the device. the chosen technique for this attack is voltage fault injection, which involves briefly dropping the device’s power supply just enough to cause it to skip instructions. ideally, the glitch should occur precisely when the device is checking the read out protection, resulting in either skipped instructions or a malformed data read.
to generate an effective voltage injection, it is very important to carefully review the target device and remove any potential sources of disruption to the glitch, such as voltage regulators, bypass capacitors, and similar components. additionally, understanding the power domain of the device is fundamental to identifying the optimal point for injecting the glitch.
power supply schema
as observed, all vdd voltage is routed through an internal voltage regulator within the soc. however, the pins vcap_1 and vcap_2 are directly connected to the core power domain, making them ideal targets for the voltage injection.
hardware preparation a cable was soldered at the vcap_1 the boot1 pin was manually forged to high to have the device starting from the system bootloader at each reboot. usart interface connected to the usb-uart ttl converted reset pin connected to the chipwhisperer tio4 important: the external uart-ttl converter is important because chipwhisperer does not support uart parity configuration.
execution once the hardware setup is properly configured, we are ready to determine the optimal glitch parameters.
however, before targeting the read out protection function within the bootloader, it is important to identify the minimum glitch settings required to induce a successful fault and cause the device to skip instructions. a simple routine like the one below can serve as a starting point:
[...] for (i = 0; i < 1000; i++) { for (j = 0; j < 1000; j++) { k++; } } print(i,k,j) [...] this routine allows us to experiment with different glitch parameters and observe the effects, helping us fine-tune the settings for successful fault injection.
identified, the parameters, repeat, width, offset, and clock frequency, we can proceed with the attack. for this particular attack, we will use the enable_only setting, which focuses solely on the repeat value and the frequency. the length of the glitch is calculated as 1/clkfreq * repeat. another important parameter to consider is the ext_offset. this value defines the waiting period before initiating the glitch and is expressed in clock cycles as 1/clkfreq. during the attack, this parameter introduced several issues, which will be explained in more detail below.
to trigger the glitch immediately after the 0x11 read command is issued, the chipwhisperer trigger pin was connected to the usart_tx line. however, we still need to determine the exact waiting time before initiating the glitch to ensure it occurs at the correct moment.
determine the ext_offset a logic analyzer was used to determine how long the command takes before being received. the logic analyzer software provides a measurement feature that is particularly useful in this case. this feature allows precise timing measurements of when the 0x11 command is transmitted and received
uart commands:
example of bootloader interactions
uart timing measurement
different measures were taken resulting in the following estimation:
command issue: 182.300 µs command response: 196.800 µs we can conclude the minimum waiting time to issue a glitch can be calculate as following:
clock cycle: 1/clkfreq== 10ns minimum waiting time: 182300/10 = 18230 clock cycle. ext_offset == number of clock cycles before issuing the glitch
glitch session the initial run using a wide ext_offset range of 18230 to 19500 resulted in several responses. after analyzing the results, i determined that the glitch was causing both the read-out protection and write protect features to have random values, resulting in a malformed environment.
after several sessions of fine-tuning and adjustments, the valid ext_offset parameter was found to be between 18300 and 18370. the script can now run:
$ python3 glitchstm32f401.py cwlite device sn = 50203220594a48303230353137303033 fw_version = major = 0 minor = 65 debug = 0 gain = mode = high gain = 30 db = 24.8359375 adc = state = true basic_mode = rising_edge timeout = 2 offset = 0 presamples = 0 samples = 5000 decimate = 1 trig_count = 433471489 fifo_fill_mode = normal clock = adc_src = clkgen_x4 adc_phase = 0 adc_freq = 29538459 adc_rate = 29538459.0 adc_locked = true freq_ctr = 0 freq_ctr_src = extclk clkgen_src = system extclk_freq = 10000000 clkgen_mul = 25 clkgen_div = 24 clkgen_freq = 100000000.0 clkgen_locked = true trigger = triggers = tio4 module = basic io = tio1 = serial_tx tio2 = serial_rx tio3 = high_z tio4 = high_z pdid = high_z pdic = high_z nrst = high_z glitch_hp = true glitch_lp = true extclk_src = hs1 hs2 = clkgen target_pwr = true tio_states = (1, 0, 1, 1) cdc_settings = bytearray(b'\x00\x00\x00\x00') glitch = clk_src = clkgen mmcm_locked = true width = 10.15625 width_fine = 0 offset = 10.15625
